INSAT-3D Satellite


INSAT-3D is a multipurpose geosynchronous satellite and a part of the Indian National Satellite System (INSAT). The INSAT system, commissioned in 1983, is a series of satellites launched by ISRO to meet India's needs for telecommunications, broadcasting, meteorology, and search and rescue. It is the largest domestic communication system in the Asia Pacific Region.

Mission and Launch
Mission Type: Multipurpose Geosynchronous Satellite

Launch Date: 2013-07-26

Launch Vehicle: Ariane 5

Launch Site: Guiana Space Centre

Primary Objectives üõ∞Ô∏è
To provide an operational, environmental, and storm warning system to protect life and property.

To monitor the earth‚Äôs surface and provide oceanic observations.

To provide data dissemination capabilities.

Payload Details
INSAT-3D is equipped with meteorological and communication payloads.

Meteorological Payloads: Includes an Imager and a Sounder.

Communication Transponders: Features 2 S-band transponders dedicated to Broadcast Satellite Services (BSS).

Ground Segment
Control Facilities: Managed from Hassan and Bhopal.

Data Acquisition and Processing: Handled at the Space Applications Centre, Bopal Campus, Ahmedabad, India.

Metadata
Source: MOSDAC, Space Applications Centre, Indian Space Research Organisation, Govt. of INDIA.

